Subjective: Stress-related symptoms: muscle tension, rapid breathing, palpitations. Correlates with demanding job as new internal medicine doctor. Feels unsure, overwhelmed by understaffing, extra shifts, long days. Experiences inner struggle, desire to say 'no' but feels obligated. Avoidant, prioritizes others' needs. Symptoms worsen with rest, spontaneous. Palpitations noticeable in neck, sometimes audible. Rapid breathing, feels like shortness of breath, occurs during rest and at work (e.g., toilet). Complaints daily for last 2 weeks, previously for months. Affects sleep: difficulty falling asleep due to worrying about next day, uncertainty. Sleeps ~6 hours/night, wakes ~6:15 AM. Sleeps better on days off. Work hours: 38hr contract, often longer days. Symptoms last ~30 mins, resolve spontaneously. No chest pain, no irregular heartbeat. No dizziness/lightheadedness. No abdominal complaints. Good support system: lives with doctor housemates, friends are doctors. ICE: Wants to rule out somatic cause (e.g., anemia). Wants to discuss with professional (practice nurse). Worried about health despite knowing it's temporary phase.
Objective: Vitals: BP 120/60, HR 65, O2 sat 98%, RR 14. Lungs: Clear, good breath sounds bilaterally. Heart: Normal heart sounds, no murmurs. No abdominal tenderness noted.
Assessment: Stress reaction to demanding work environment. Symptoms of anxiety/stress manifesting physically (palpitations, rapid breathing). Rule out somatic causes (anemia, thyroid, renal/hepatic dysfunction) via blood tests. No acute distress or concerning physical findings on exam.
Plan:
1. Blood test: CBC (hemoglobin), TSH, LFTs, RFTs to rule out somatic causes. Results in 2 working days, available via portal/phone.
2. Refer to Mental Health Nurse Practitioner for counseling, appointment can be made today.
3. Lifestyle advice: Actively build in relaxation moments, activities that give energy (coffee, call friend, walk, swim). Maintain regularity (sleep/wake times). Consider Occupational Health Service at hospital for tips/schedule adjustments.
4. Safety netting: Return for appointment if symptoms worsen or concerns arise after practice nurse consultation or blood test results.
5. Follow-up: Review blood test results. Assess progress after practice nurse consultation.
